<h2>A LOW FAT DIET</h2>
<p> fat intake at about 1/3 of the total daily calories consumed<br><br><br>

diet plan to reduce obesity focuses on foods that contain whole grains, fruits and vegetables. <br><br><br>

It is directed towards weight loss<br><br><br>

Plenty of vegetables and proteins in a typical low fat diet supply the body with energy but very little fats.
</p>

<h2>FOOD TO EAT</h2>
<p>Choose minimally processed, whole foods:<br><br><br>

Whole grains (whole wheat, steel cut oats, brown rice, quinoa) <br><br><br>

Vegetables (a colorful variety-not potatoes) <br><br><br>

Whole fruits (not fruit juices) <br><br><br>

Nuts, seeds, beans, and other healthful sources of protein (fish and poultry) <br><br><br>

Plant oils (olive and other vegetable oils) <br><br><br>

Drink water or other beverages that are naturally calorie-free<br><br><br>
</p>
<h2>DO'S</h2>
<p>
Eat more vegetables - add them at every meal. <br><br><br>


Drink plenty of water - you can become hungry when thirsty. <br><br><br>


Exercise between 30 minutes to one hour each day with moderate exercise - brisk walking, team sport, cycling or swimming.


</p>
<h2>DONT'S</h2>
<p>
Rely on soft drinks, sweetened cereals, cookies and cakes, donuts and pastries, chips<br><br><br>

Don't skip meals. <br><br><br>

Don't food shop when you're hungry.


</p>
